SIMPLE: inner
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Inner
<hw>In"ner</hw> <pr>(⟦icr⟧n"n⟦etil⟧r)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[AS.
<ets>innera</ets>, a compar. fr. <ets>inne</ets> within, fr.
<ets>in</ets> in. See <er>In</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Further in;
interior; internal; not outward; <as>as, an <ex>inner</ex>
chamber</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Of or pertaining to the spirit or its
phenomena.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>This attracts the soul,⟦br⟧
Governs the <qex>inner</qex> man, the nobler part.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Not obvious or easily discovered; obscure.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Inner house</b></col> <fld>(Scot.)</fld>, <cd>the first
and second divisions of the court of Session at Edinburgh; also, the
place of their sittings.</cd> -- <col><b>Inner jib</b></col>
<fld>(Naut.)</fld>, <cd>a fore-and-aft sail set on a stay running from
the fore-topmast head to the jib boom.</cd> -- <col><b>Inner
plate</b></col> <fld>(Arch.)</fld>, <cd>the wall plate which lies
nearest to the center of the roof, in a double-plated roof.</cd> --
<col><b>Inner post</b></col> <fld>(Naut.)</fld>, <cd>a piece brought on
at the fore side of the main post, to support the transoms.</cd> --
<col><b>Inner square</b></col> <fld>(Carp.)</fld>, <cd>the angle formed
by the inner edges of a carpenter's square.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Innerly</ent>⟦br⟧
